  <p class="text-center">Exhibited between May 1802 – April 1803 at Leicester Square in the Lower Circle.<a href="#citation1"><sup>[1]</sup></a></p>
  <hr>
  <h1 class="text-center text-2xl leading-6 mb-4 uppercase"><span>Lord Nelson'<span class="lowercase">s</span></span><br><span class="text-4xl font-bold">Attack of Copenhagen.</span></h1>
  <p class="text-center text-xl">~~~~~~~~~~~~</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Fort of Amak, which fired Shot and Shells at the Commencement of the Action.</li>
    <li>Rigged Prams serving as floating Batteries, one of which was sunk in action.</li>
    <li>Remains of the Royal Palace formerly burnt.</li>
    <li>Quintus Battery, which kept up a constant Fire upon the English Line.</li>
    <li>The Arsenal, into which some Shells were thrown, and a Part set on Fire but without doing much damage.</li>
    <li>The great Crane at the Entrance of the Arsenal.</li>
    <li>End of the Lines which fortify Copenhagen.</li>
    <li>Small Crown Battery without Guns.</li>
    <li>Great or Three Crown Battery, from which a most dreadful Fire was kept up during the whole Action. This battery mounted 88 Guns, 36 and 24 Pounders.</li>
    <li>The Point leading to Elsinoer and opening of the Sound.</li>
    <li>Huin Island, which gave Birth to the famous Tycho Brahe.</li>
    <li>Sir Hyde Parker's Division.</li>
    <li>Floating Batteries, mounting 24 Pounders, &amp;c.</li>
  </ol>
  <p class="text-center text-xl">~~~~~~~~~~~~</p>
  <p class="text-center italic">Lord Nelson's First Letter, sent with a Flag of Truce.</p>
  <p><span class="uppercase">Lord Nelson</span> has Directions to spare Denmark when no longer resisting; but, if the Firing is continued on the Part of Denmark, <span style="font-variant: small-caps">Lord Nelson</span> will be obligated to set on Fire all the Floating Batteries he has taken, without having the Power of saving the brave Danes who have defended them. Dated on board his Britannic Majesty's Ship Elephant, Copenhagen Roads, April 2, 1801.</p>
  <p>To the Brothers of Englishmen, the Danes.</p>
  <p class="text-right">(Signed) <span class="uppercase">Nelson</span> and <span class="uppercase">Bronte</span>, Vice Admiral under the Command of Admiral Sir <span class="uppercase">Hyde Parker</span>.</p>
  <p><span class="italic">Answer</span>.—His Royal Highness the Prince Royal of Denmark has sent me, General Adjutant Lindholm, on board to his Britannic Majesty's Vice Admiral, the Right Honourable <span style="font-variant: small-caps">Lord Nelson</span>, to ask the particular Object of sending the Flag of Truce.</p>
  <p class="text-center uppercase">Lord Nelson'<span class="lowercase">s</span> Reply.</p>
  <p><span style="font-variant: small-caps">Lord Nelson</span> Object in sending on shore a Flag of Truce, is <span class="italic">Humanity</span>; therefore consents that Hostilities shall cease till <span style="font-variant: small-caps">Lord Nelson</span> can take <span class="italic">his</span> Prisoners cut of the Prizes; and <span class="italic">he</span> consents to land all the wounded Danes, and to burn or remove <span class="italic">his</span> Prizes. <span style="font-variant: small-caps">Lord Nelson</span>, with humble Duty to his Royal Highness, begs Leave to say, that he will ever esteem it the greatest Victory he ever gained, if this Flag of Truce may be the happy forerunner of a lasting and happy Union between my most Gracious Sovereign and his Majesty the King of Denmark.</p>
  <p>To the Government of Denmark.</p>
  <p class="text-right">(Signed) <span class="uppercase">Nelson</span> and <span class="uppercase">Bronte</span>.</p>
  <p><span style="font-variant: small-caps">General Lindholm</span> immediately requested of <span style="font-variant: small-caps">Lord Nelson</span> to hoist the Flag of Truce; and he, in his Royal Highness's Name, acquiesced in the Terms which his Lordship had demanded.</p>
  <p class="text-center text-xl">~~~~~~~~~~~~</p>
  <p>Mr. <span class="uppercase">Barker</span>, ever desirous to have his Representations completely correct, entreated of <span style="font-variant: small-caps">Lord Nelson</span> to inspect, at the <span style="font-variant: small-caps">Panorama</span>, the Painting of the <span style="font-variant: small-caps">Battle</span> of <span style="font-variant: small-caps">Copenhagen</span>, previous to its being opened for Exhibition, and has been honoured with the following flattering Testimony by <span style="font-variant: small-caps">His Lordship</span>:—</p>
  <p>"<span class="uppercase">Sir</span>, <span class="uppercase">I have</span> acceded to your Request, and seen the Picture which you intend to exhibit of the <span style="font-variant: small-caps">Battle</span> of <span style="font-variant: small-caps">Copenhagen</span>; and, making due Allowances for the Alteration of the Positions of many of the Ships, in the Space of One Hour and a Half, which Time I consider the Picture to embrace, I have no Scruple in saying, that I consider it the most correct Picture of any Event I have ever seen; and I believe Captain <span style="font-variant: small-caps">Foley</span>, and the Hon. Col. <span style="font-variant: small-caps">Stewart</span>, who have examined the Picture with me, are of the same Opinion.</p>
  <p class="text-right">I am, <span style="font-variant: small-caps">Sir</span>, <span style="font-variant: small-caps">Mr.</span> <span class="uppercase">Barker</span>, <span style="font-variant: small-caps">Panorama</span>. Your most obedient Servant, <span class="uppercase">Nelson</span> and <span class="uppercase">Bronte</span>."</p>
  <hr>
  <p id="citation1"><sup>[1]</sup> <em>The First Panoramas: Visions of British Imperialism</em> by Denise Oleksijczuk, p. 173</p>
